description.text:
Rebuilt based on CloudMaker's version (which is  based on the sculpture LOVE by Robert Indiana).  
Now the letters slightly overlap, making the print less fragile.  
Done with OpenSCAD. The single letters are in a dxf and then extruded, so you easily can do some finetuning if you want to.

author: drayde

description.text: Your students will create a bracelet that expresses their personal style and learn about the business side of 3D printing. As a culminating activity, the students can share their bracelet designs, 3D printing knowledge, and business acumen in an innovation expo for the school, community, and business partners.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

Varies

Notes:

Small - 7 inches long
Medium - 8 inches long
Large - 9 inches long
Remove raft and wear!

In this project, students will learn about how businesses work by customizing designs for a 3d printed bracelet and developing an abbreviated business plan for pitching the bracelet in a trade show setting. This project is part of a financial literacy/entrepreneurship unit that gives students a hand-on experience in developing a product to sell. The other parts of the unit include:
  • Conducting market research on target market and evaluating data in findings.
    Student teams will use Google Forms to create a marketing survey for their target market, distribute and collect surveys from twenty potential customers, and analyze the data collected in Google Spreadsheets.
  • Designing a bracelet that sells.
    Student teams will create a bracelet using MakerBot Desktop to customize a template using the scale, infills, and other customization features. Student will print using a 3D printer and complete post-production modifications. Student will collect cost information, set a price for the bracelet, and calculate contribution margin and breakeven quantity in units.
  • Computing the profit and financials.
    Student teams will use Google Sheets to develop breakeven analysis, sales projections, and profit and loss statements for the customized bracelet.
  • Pitch the bracelet in a trade show setting.
    Students will participate in an innovation expo where they will use a 3’ by 2’ tabletop space to market their bracelet with marketing materials and informative signage. Each student on the team will develop a 30 second elevator pitch for the expo. Bracelet design, marketing materials, booth setup, and elevator pitch will be judged by a panel of judges drawn from the neighborhood and business communities.
    • Objectives Students will be able to:
  • Work collaboratively with team members to solve a problem.
  • Develop a creative custom design for 3D printing.
  • Explain the steps in a process.
  • Communicate the features and benefits of their design in an Innovation Expo judged by community and business partners
    • Audience 6-12 grade students. Student should be comfortable using Windows or Mac/OS, and copying, pasting, and manipulating images with a mouse. Subject Art
    Applied Mathematics
    Business
    Computer Science
    Entrepreneurship
    Economics
    Financial Literacy Skills Learned (Standards) ISTE National Educational Technology Standards for Students (NETS-S)
  • Critical thinking, problem solving, and decision making Students use critical thinking skills to plan and conduct research, manage projects, solve problems, and make informed decisions using appropriate digital tools and resources.
    a. Identify and define authentic problems and significant questions for investigation
    b. Plan and manage activities to develop a solution or complete a project
    c. Collect and analyze data to identify solutions and/or make informed decisions
    • NBEA Standards for Entrepreneurship
    II. Marketing
    Achievement Standard: Analyze customer groups and develop a plan to identify, reach, and keep customers in a specific target market. V. Accounting
    Achievement Standard: Recognize that entrepreneurs must establish, maintain, and analyze appropriate records to make business decisions. IX. Business Plans
    Achievement Standard: Develop a business plan.

Extensions Student can extend their learning by trying the following suggestions for other bracelet designs:
  • Make alphabet links and spell out words.
  • Print each link in the bracelet in a different color.

title: Fusematic e3d Clip
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The default e3d clip that comes with the Fusematic Printer causes the heat block to rub on the v-rail if positioned incorrectly. This can cause some problems, especially for newer owners of the printer if they do not know what to look for. This new clip lowers and brings forward the e3d hotend to keep it away from the v-rail and also to add a few mm of space from the z coupler if attached too high.

I suggest printing in ABS or PETG as this part is in direct contact with the hotend and if not properly cooled will melt if printed in PLA. It can be used in PLA, but I would advise against it.

author: Wasatch

description.text:
This is a wall mount for the Bluetooth speaker Creative Soundblaster Free.
My first shoot at designing 3D so still needs some tweaks like the holes for the screws.

Printed in PLA no Raft and no Support just active cooling.

I doing some testing and I needed an over/under extrusion test I can repeat with different settings without wasting hours or tons of material - so I designed this little thing.

It uses about one gram of filament and takes 7 minutes to print - and you can know if you have over or under extrusion without any tools.

Print with 0% infill and 1.2mm shell thickness (3 shells) for 0.4mm nozzle, wait for it to cool down before taking it off the build plate.

This specifically tests edge extrusion, all the corners are rounded to a avoid corner over extrusion and the bottom is slightly tapered to avoid any measuring problem due to the first layer (that often bulges a bit because it is squished to improve adhesion).

To test with calipers: print one, measure to inner and outer part (see image) if the outer part is bigger the difference is your over extrusion, if the inner part is bigger the difference is your under extrusion.

To test with no tools: print two, they should fit together perfectly (see image) and stay connected, if they don't fit you have over extrusion, if there's space between them you have under extrusion.

Update:

@gork made a calculator you can plug the actual measurements of this model printed on your printer and it will give you the flow value you need to set in order to compensate for over/under extrusion.

Another Update

Check out my other calibration piece at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2753088

comments.text: My outer dimension is around .5 mm larger than the inside dimension. The calculator says I need to reduce the extrusion multiplier to 0.75 but then I am definitely under extruding since the layers start separating and there are holes everywhere. Any ideas?
comments.author: Nilz

comments.text: I had no idea I was out by so much!  I'm pretty new and my prints were acceptable but had some annoying things that made me wonder if I was over-extruding.  I printed these and they didn't even come close to fitting together.  Using that calculator, it told me to change from 1 to 0.75!  I may have a few more iterations to go through and we'll see where things settle... but I wanted to say thanks for the Thing and the clear instructions.
comments.author: bcsteeve

comments.text: Five iterations later... it settled on 80% and man, those fit so perfectly together I drool - just a bit.
comments.author: bcsteeve

comments.text: important to note that the multiplier varies from:
comments.author: diigbluh

comments.text:
OK, so my outer extrusion is 9.8 mm, and my inner extrusion is 10.1 mm, that means I have a .3 under extrusion right?
Now what?
comments.author: mfuse

comments.text: My other comment got flagged for moderation for some darn reason, but while I greatly appreciate @NirDobovizki producing this model (it is a GREAT calibration piece!), I strongly disagree with him that in your case you should not make adjustments to improve. In fact, if underextrusion is your only problem and you are using a 0.4mm nozzle and 0.42mm extrusion width (assumed), you are underextruding by a very large margin and need to adjust your extrusion multiplier to 1.56! There is a lot of room for measurement error here so you want to be very careful making yorur measurements that you are accurate.
comments.author: mfuse

comments.text: Hi, I actually agree with you.
comments.author: gork

comments.text: I disagree quote a bit with @NirDobovizki here. It is possible to control the extrusion widths to a much greater precision than 0.2mm on hobby level printers. I was referred to this model because I suspected some slight overextrusion and this was referenced as a good test object. My machine was out by approximately the measurements you specify and making a couple of small test iterations these objects now fit together perfectly and I am now out about 20 microns which is close now the tolerances of both my machine and my calipers.
comments.author: mfuse

comments.text: Your lines are off by 0.1/0.2mm, that's perfectly acceptable for most things you can print on an home 3d printer anyway, it could be a slicing rounding error, it could even be the accuracy limitation of your printer's mechanics or the device you used to measure the part - I would leave everything as is unless there are other more visible quality problems.
comments.author: mfuse

comments.author: Hammersquash

description.text: Customized version of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:58001 Created with Customizer! http://www.thingiverse.com/apps/customizer/run?thing_id=58001

This fellow looks out from the peak of the Sioux Falls Coliseum. When I first noticed him, I knew he was some type of deity from mythology based on his crown and classical appearance. I assumed he was Poseidon (or his Latin counterpart Neptune). I found out from research at the local historical society that he is supposed to be Boreas (Aquilon is his Latin counterpart) the North Wind. It is a little odd since he actually looks eastward!

You can see him from N. Dakota Avenue in the 500 block just north of the immediate downtown area.

I took 39 photographs with a simple point and shoot Canon as the sun began to set behind the Coliseum. While it did eliminate the harsh shadows and blown highlights, the resulting photographs weren't very good for modeling with. I still persevered and was able to create a somewhat crude 3D model.

I ran the photos through Photoscan on the medium setting at all points. I found the original model was extremely noisy and I had to work hard to decimate and smooth the worst of the grain and noise away.

My goal is to use new photos with a few telephoto lenses to get better photographs and model this interesting architectural decoration with better detail.

author: herenkeskin

description.text:
Played at Ion in 2016. I need a camera mount that didn't stick out from the side of my head like a telephone pole. I also wanted to protect the camera from paintball hits.

Some advice about capturing video. Gun cam's are fun for that one awesome shot but they spend a lot of time recording the ground. At least thats true in scenario games. If it's going to be running at least capture some of the insane stuff others do. Or get a great blooper clip.

To that end I mounted mine on my mask. To get good video place the camera on the opposite side of your shooting hand. If you don't you will have a bunch of video of the back of your gun. Most people sight down the barrel when they shoot.

There are 2 holes you will need to drill in your mask. It can be mounted on either side of your mask. All the nut traps are for M3 nuts.

I have added a washer / gromit for the back side of the mask. On the softer materials the m3 screws pull through. Put the screw through the washer, the hole in the mask and into the camera mount.

You wont be able to tell if the Camera is not exactly at eye level. Having it at you jaw line or at the top of your ear will not make a lot of difference.

DO NOT DRILL ANY PART OF THE LENSE!!!!
DO NOT DRILL ANY PART OF THE LENSE!!!!
You will be in violation of the NPPL's safety rules and NO field will let you play with that mask.

Parts
3 M3 Nuts
2 M3x10mm Socket cap screws
1 M3x25

Drop me a line if you have issues.
Update: February 5, 2017
Improved description
Add STEP files

Update: October 8 2016
Add a left and right ver with no holes on the opposite side. This was for those who could mirror the part in there slicer.
Added an M3 washer / grommet. M3 screw pulled through on some of the softer materials.

title: Quadcopter electronics stack mount (flight controller, power module, receiver)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is my attempt to create a mounting bracket for electronics part of my quadcopter. Design goal was to hold flight controller, receiver and power module, and fit everything into the center of a small F330 frame.

There are three things:

  • fc_base: lower part that holds the BEC power module and FrSky receiver. Mounted to the copter base plate (50mm mounting holes). I used additional nuts as spacers so that a battery strap fits under it.
  • fc_mount: middle part that holds the flight controller (also adapts from 50mm to 30mm mounting holes)
  • fc_cover: upper part that covers and fixates the flight controller

Here are links to the electronics parts I used:

  • NAZE32 F3 Flight Controller
  • FrSky X4R-SB Receiver
  • APM power module with BEC

I mounted it on a F330 Frame by drilling holes for nylon screws to the bottom plate.

This thing is in progress. Everything seems to fit together well, but there's probably room for more improvements.

description.text:
I used Inkscape and GIMP to process the original image source (in-game symbol of the Argonians). Then, I modelled the pendant in Blender.

Argonians (in their native tongue of Jel they call themselves the Saxhleel, or People of the Root) are the reptilian natives of Black Marsh, a vast swampland province in southeastern Tamriel. The other races often prefer to refer to them as ‘lizards’ or the ‘Lizard Folk’ instead, especially when meaning to be derogative. They are known as the foremost experts in guerrilla warfare throughout the Starry Heart, a reputation brought upon them by defending their borders from enemies for countless centuries. Argonians have a lifespan similar to that of humans. According to the First Era Scholar Brendan the Persistent “the Argonian people have, throughout Tamrielic history, been perhaps the most misunderstood, vilified, and reviled of all the sentient races. Yet, those who have taken the time to experience Argonian culture have gained a greater appreciation for this noble and beautiful people". However, it should be noted that he himself went missing in his final expedition into the deeper swamps of their homeland.

I used Inkscape and GIMP to process the original image source (in-game symbol of the Aldmeri Dominion). Then, I modelled the pendant in Blender.

The Aldmeri Dominion refers to any of at least three separate empires established by the Altmer on the continent of Tamriel over the course of its history. The term "Aldmeri" is literally translated as "Home of the Elves". The original Aldmeri Dominion, also known as the First Dominion, was an empire founded by Queen Ayrenn in 2E 580, in the midst of the Interregnum. The Second Dominion was formed in 2E 830 when the Summerset Isles conquered Valenwood over a dynastic dispute. The Oblivion Crisis that ended the Third Era and weakened the Empire provided the opportunity for the Third Aldmeri Dominion to form. The Thalmor, who had survived as a marginalized political faction that espoused Elven superiority, painted themselves as the saviors of the Summerset Isles during the Crisis. The Altmer public believed these claims, and with the Empire too disarrayed to reassert its authority, the Thalmor's popularity swelled. In 4E 22, the Thalmor solidified their position and seized total control of the Summerset Isles, renaming it Alinor. Seven years later, a Thalmor-backed coup overthrew Valenwood's government, routing Imperial forces and their Bosmer supporters. Alinor and Valenwood then proclaimed a union, and the Aldmeri Dominion was reborn.

New in this version:
  • Updated the drawings to make the servo arm lign up better with the switch
  • Made a wooden board to build the electronics
  • Made the box a bit better
  • Implemented spacers to hold the microswitch.
  • Made a parts list [EDIT: See comments for link to the parts list, this was an old feature of Thingiverse]...
  • Used flat cable as the connecting wire for the flip switch to avoid multiple wires (or thick round wires).

Lasercut the parts from 3mm wood (except for the \"circuit board\" which needs 1mm wood). Assemble the electronics on the 1mm wooden board (or however you prefer), put the servo in the designated hole, connect all the wires and assemble the box. If you mount a microswitch of the same type I made room for, use 6 of the spacers included on sheet 2 to give it the proper distance from the mounting board in the box (3 on each M3 screw). Remember to glue/tape/fasten the flat cable running from the switch, so it doesn't come off after too much fiddling to align everything... The wooden arm should hit the switch when mounted with small screws to the servo arm, but I've had varying degrees of luck with returning the arm to the correct position where the lid closes all the way, so YMMV... By the way: All credit goes to Saskview on Instructables
http://www.instructables.com/id/The-Most-Useless-Machine/

title: 1156 / 1157 Bulb Diffuser
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
https://stupidbus.wordpress.com/

https://stupidbus.wordpress.com/2016/06/11/on-cheap-fixes-baby/

A diffuser for 1156 or 1157 bulbs. My turn signal lenses on my VW Beetle were bleaching clear, and white turn signals are annoying and dangerous, as well as illegal in most states. Printed with translucent orange filament, this makes them a nice amber. Fits well over my tall 1156 COB LED bulbs.

For best results, print with no infill and one shell. More shells will darken the light output.

Solidworks file included if you want to edit the model (change/remove the hole, etc).

Also fits over incandescent bulbs, but in that application, they are for turn signal use only to avoid melting the print.

comments.text: The probe is for holding a part in location on the board prior to soldering. For a thru-hole IC, it prevents the IC from falling out when the board is flipped upside down for soldering. For a surface mount part, it keeps the part from moving out of location while getting it tacked into place.

title: The Ultimate Light Pull - Bright Man

description.text:
Have trouble remembering which pull-cord is the light and which one's the fan? Finding all the "FAN" and "LIGHT" pulls a little too generic for your tastes? Well now there's this!
See also the companion piece, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1628941

For this project you will need:
a standard 16mm marble (5/8"), clear (or whatever color you like), available at any dollar store or most upper-echelon toy stores
a tube of E6000 ("Household Goop"), available at most decent craft stores
a fan with a light pull chain (1/8" ball chain seems to be the standard)
Glue the marble into the threads on top of Bright Man's Head. Then disconnect the chain from your fan, thread it through his fist, and reconnect. Done!

If you don't have a proper chain-end, or you don't like yours, you can use the attached "Washer" to terminate the chain dangling from your fan.
The head and gut were free-modeled based on a google image search; the arms and legs were from a DeviantArt model, posed in XNALara, and edited together in Blender.

description.text:
I used Inkscape and GIMP to process the original image source (in-game symbol of the Atmoran Bear). Then, I modelled the pendant in Blender.

The Bear is the totemic aspect of the Ancient Nord god Orkey, who seem to have taken up his worship during Aldmeri rule of Atmora. He combines aspects of Malacath and Arkay. According to Imperial scholars, the Nords believe they once lived as long as Elves until Orkey appeared; through heathen trickery, he fooled them into a bargain that "bound them to the count of winters", and the Nordic lifespan was reduced to six years due to Orkey's foul magic. Through unknown means, Shor showed up and removed the curse, throwing most of it onto the nearby Orcs.

title: LED TV mount support for VESA 200mm

description.text:
This is my first design from scratch. It's made to support a 32" LED TV with VESA 200mm. It weights about 20lbs (the TV..) It's up to you if you want to use it, I'm not responsible for any fallen TVs ;). I had to cut it in 4 main pieces so it fits my printer bed of 200x200.

I tested it by applying a moderate DOWN pulling force on the TV while mounted and I didn't hear any weird sound so I'm pretty sure it's safe, or maybe almost sure. DON'T apply much horizontal pulling force, I'm pretty sure it's not gonna be good. It's designed to be strong vertically.

It's been on the wall for 1 week on June 13th and still no scary noises when pulling down moderately. Everything seems ok.

I used only the two top screws for attaching to the wall, you can use the two bottom ones in addition for more sturdiness.

I used 16 M3 screws and nuts + glue to secure the parts together. The screws I used in the wall were coming with another TV support bought from the store a while ago. Don't forget to use attachment plugs in the gypsum walls for extra strength. I also put some soft auto-sticking pads behind the support to make sure the TV screws don't scratch the wall during installation. It took about 120g of PLA to make all the parts.

Please note that the part that's going on the TV isn't totally flat, the cross in the middle is 1.2mm over the lips. It wasn't a problem for me since the TV screwing sockets were a little higher than the flat surface. Just ask me if you need it to be flat, I'll modify the files for you. Also tell me if you need more detailed assembly instructions.

Enjoy!

print_settings.Notes:: Use whatever setting you normally do but make sure to use support unless you can bridge about 40mm.

description.text:
I wanted something to cool the plastic as it comes out of the nozzle but didn't want it to be bulky since my printers is somewhat small and didn't want to make the usable volume even smaller. So I replaced the stock piece with my own and the stock fan with a 40mm one. Basically it's the stock piece but at the bottom air is directed towards the nozzle.

Note: I have my fan set at 60% for perimeters and 30% for infill at 80% or so, depending on the fan, the hotend can be cooled so much that it won't be able to reach the temperature you want.

Update: Added a second version that should be easier to remove support from, isn't as close to the heater block, has exit slots if the back is blocked, and directs air more towards the nozzle though it will be somewhat harder for air to move through.

I'm designer for shapeways here: https://www.shapeways.com/designer/jonathanmarch/hire-me

Printer Brand:

Solidoodle

Printer:

Solidoodle 2 - Expert

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

25%

Notes:

Use whatever setting you normally do but make sure to use support unless you can bridge about 40mm.

IMPORTANT

If the hotend is hot and the fan is off the PTFE tube inside (if there is one, there is for 1.75mm) can soften and make the hotend unusable so either always make sure to have it on or you can change marlin a bit. Under MarlinMain replace the block of code that is similiar to this, about line number 1163
#if FAN_PIN > -1
case 106: //M106 Fan On
if (code_seen('S')){
fanSpeed=constrain(code_value(),0,255);
if(fanSpeed<minFanSpeed)
{
fanSpeed=minFanSpeed;
}
}
else {
fanSpeed=255;
}
break;
case 107: //M107 Fan Off
fanSpeed = minFanSpeed;
break;
#endif //FAN_PIN
also where fanSpeed is defined, about line number 172, replace with
int minFanSpeed = 100;
int fanSpeed=minFanSpeed;
then set minFanSpeed to what you want

Installation

Remove the support and screw a fan onto it, flip it upside down, then it snap it on the hotend, mine is one fin from the top.

Attention: This Thing was fraudulently entered and won second place in a recent Reddit hosted Lulzbot contest by Reddit user Blink_182 aka Hasan El-Hasan. Do not attempt to pass off my original work as your own!
Full size Soprano Ukulele with 13.875" scale length. Bracing, bridge plate & bridge are all one piece with the body. Pre-slotted nut & frets are all one piece with the neck. The neck fits into the body via a dovetail, without any glue. Tuning pegs are "violin" friction style.
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zoiIoK4jrdc
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vd7Ztnq8kG4

Printed on a Stratasys 1200es. Originals printed in ABSplus .010" resolution with SOLID infill. I cannot guarantee any other plastic working under string tension and any other infill.
Print the body back side down. Print the neck fingerboard side up. Print the tuning pegs (four required) with one side of the shaft flat to the print plate (I have found they are less likely to slip in this orientation).
Hopefully this doesn't happen to you, but I have had issues with ABS warpage while printing the neck. The dovetail area warped so much that it affected the fit into the body. I have had to take a chisel and re-fit the neck to the body. Cut only the face of the neck that touches the body, NOT the sides of the dovetail, and focus on the heel cap area (small end). It is very easy to screw up the string height while doing this, as well as intonation, be aware. You may need to trim the bottom face of the dovetail and in turn will probably need to wrap paper shims around the back and sides of the dovetail if you alter the fit. No glue required if a tight fit is achieved.
To assemble place the back flat on a table, place the end of the neck into the body dovetail and one good strong push should set the neck. If you need to remove it place the heel cap on a table edge, keep it level and grab either side of the body around the neck with your thumbs and push down on the body.
The finished ukuleles pictured are versions I & II. I do not have the funds/interest to print and test more. This version uses a less traditional bracing system seen in version I because it sounds better than the more traditional bracing found in version II. I have not tested the fit of the finished tuning peg so I include a blank which will allow you to add your own 1/16" hole and trim to length if necessary. The body was designed with a soluble support material in mind with a drainage hole near the neck block. I may add a version with a separate top soon when I have more time.

title: Dial Indicator Mount for Monoprice Select Mini

description.text:
This component replaces the back plate of this dial indicator (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B016R3GLB0/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1) and and temporarily mounts to the heatsink on the print head of the Monoprice Select Mini. The fan must be removed and either dangled or set on top of the X-axis cover. Due to the extra weight of the dial indicator, I recommend using it between 0.6" and 0.7", because in this range the return force of the internal spring roughly equals the weight of the indicator, thereby relieving the X- and Z-axes of the additional stress.

I plan to improve the design, but as it stands now, this works.

title: Grease catcher for George Foreman grill

description.text: I inherited a used George Foreman grill but it didn't have the grease catcher.  I've been using it over the edge of the sink, but why not print a new grease tray?

The big trick with printing this is that it's so long and thin, so you have lots of long strands cooling and causing massive amounts of curl, enough to cause the layers to crack.  I made the sides thinner and shorter, and you will have to adjust your slicer settings to be sure the infill even on solid layers is at a 45 degree angle to the sides.  (On my Solidoodle 3, I had to print this diagonally to make it fit well, which means I needed slicer settings at 90 degrees.)  Even so, I had a bit of curl causing one crack I sealed up with model glue and a clamp, since after a half-dozen failed prints I didn't want to try yet again.

Inspired by WindowFarms which you can learn all about at www.windowfarms.com  
This is a hydroponic growing system that uses basic aquarium equipment.

To print: 1 x BaseTanks
1 x TankCover
1 x TankTubeHolder
1 x TubeHolder
n x MainHolder
n x Basket where n is the number of plants you want in the stack. Recommend 1-4. Needed to complete:
1 x aquarium pump
Aquarium tubing
T-coupler
Flow control valve
One-way check valve
Daily plug-in timer
Kite string Much of the information can be found here: http://www.windowfarms.com/build-your-own/ You'll need to do you're own research on growing media, plants, and nutrient solutions. I'm still a novice, so I don't want to misguide anyone. I'm using a mixture of clay ball, perlite, coconut coir for my media and Botanicare CNS17 Hydro Formula Grow for my nutrient solution. Pictured is sweet basil and cilantro. [EDITED: this is no longer valid. See below] A key point I found to ensure you get pumping of the water up the tubing to the top is to make sure the bottom opening of the T-connector that is open to the nutrient solution in the base is pointed down and as deep as you can get it in the tank, which is why I created the TankTubeHolder and glued (with cyanoacrylate) it to the bottom of the tank. [EDIT] I ended up drilling a hole towards the bottle of the tank and epoxying a tube in place to feed the water to the air lift T-joint, which is now outside the tank. See the new photo and video of the air lift system. Let me know if you have any questions. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OCN4mh9lhUE

description.text:
I added the Wanhao 120mm PSU cover http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1590987, but still had a lot of noise from my power supply fan. The 120mm should provide enough airflow for control box and power supply, so I took the cover the power supply and removed the fan. I replaced the cover with this vented cover to keep stray wires out of the power supply and to keep a good airflow.

There is a 3mm thing version of the case hooks and a 1mm version. I used 3mm, since I wanted to have a more solid cover. I just bent out the tabs on the case to hook into the hooks.

Messing with a power supply will void its warranty and contains a risk of shock. Be very wary of this upgrade and only do it if the unit is unplugged from power and you know what you are doing.

Make sure to transfer your wiring diagram sticker from the old cover to the new cover if you want to keep the diagram.

I included the 123d files if you want to tweak.

This shield still allow the CPU to breath, but prevent dust and water mist or droplets from falling directly into the vent holes.

title: RC4wd Trailfinder 2 Mojave Front Body Mount

description.text:
Front body mount for Mojave. I didn't enjoy having to constantly remove the screws on the side of the body to get inside the chassis. This method seems to work well. There is also a mount to offset 12mm down.

title: Adafruit Trinket wire organizer and holder

description.text:
This is the first part of a series of things I made for an upcoming music festival.

I wanted to make sure I had backup Trinkets in case something went wrong. So I created a little "card" and a holder I will post later that attaches to a PVC tube.

With 3 of these wired up and ready to go I can quickly detach the clips and pull the card out and slide a new one in and keep it all going. Or I could write different programs on all the cards and swap them as needed.

print_settings.Notes:: Used PLA.  Note: The incandescent bulb get's hot and may melt PLA.  Use a higher temp filament or LED lamps.

description.text: This is a license plate light cover for a Ford Pickup. The cover broke off from the bulb socket and was lost. I couldn't find a replacement of the same type locally so I made one.

Printer Brand:

Printrbot

Printer:

Simple Black

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

2.6 mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Used PLA. Note: The incandescent bulb get's hot and may melt PLA. Use a higher temp filament or LED lamps.

NOTICE: The incandescent lamp gets hot and may melt PLA. I installed LED lamps.

This is just the cover to replace a broken and lost cover. The infill was removed and test fitted on the broken socket. The part was spray painted silver to closer match the excising light. I hot glued a piece of clear plastic over the inside of the opening. The clear plastic came from the package of a 1156 light bulb that I found in the garage. I cut a rounded piece that was the right shape. If your not using an LED, a regular lamp may also melt this plastic.

The cover was then hot glued to the end of the broken socket, then installed in the bumper.

I took measurements of the existing cover and the broken socket. I created the part out of rectangles. I used "tweak" and "fillet" to get the general shape. I copied this, scaled one copy smaller, then subtracted the smaller copy to get the void in the inside.

I modeled the broken lamp holder and subtracted this from the inside to make a surface to glue the cover to the broken socket.

It's not an exact match, but close. I made this just for an old truck, and it looks good in the dark!

Tsing Ma Bridge in Wikipedia:
Tsing Ma Bridge is a bridge in Hong Kong.[1] It is the world's ninth-longest span suspension bridge, and was the second longest at time of completion.[2] The bridge was named after two of the islands at its ends, namely Tsing Yi and Ma Wan. It has two decks and carries both road and rail traffic, which also makes it the largest suspension bridge of this type. The bridge has a main span of 1,377 metres (4,518 ft) and a height of 206 metres (676 ft). The span is the largest of all bridges in the world carrying rail traffic.
The 41-metre (135 ft) wide bridge deck carries six lanes of automobile traffic, with three lanes in each direction. The lower level contains two rail tracks and two sheltered carriageways, used for maintenance access and traffic lanes when particularly severe typhoons strike Hong Kong and the bridge deck is closed to traffic.

title: Linear Insulator for KLM KT34 Antenna

description.text:
A friend reached out to me as they knew someone who needed replacement linear insulators for an antenna they were trying to repair. I was provided with a single insulator, which was cracked due to weather and age, and from this I was able to use a caliper and generate something resembling this insulator.

The top ring is a bit thicker than the actual model as it seemed that was where the cracking had occurred. I have printed a batch of them out of PETG material at about 80-90% infill. They have not been installed as of yet, but we will see how well they weather!

You can find a copy of the manual (as well as a better representation of the part) here: http://www.hamanuals.com/MMans/KLM83.pdf

This is an enclosure for an Adafruit Feather that features an opening for a 1.44" Color TFT, Vibrating Mini Motor Disk, SPST Slide Switch, 3.7V LIION Battery (all from Adafruit), and two momentary contact switches with switch cover. The enclosure has a snap fit that holds the bottom in place. There is an opening for a USB to connect and charge the battery without opening the case.

This is part of a larger project sill in progress. This is being shared for others who may be looking for an enclosure for similar components. The Feather used for this project is the Feather 32u4 with RFM69HCW Radio Module. This unit is used to monitor the status of several sensors using the RFM69HCW radio.

As always, I have included the 123D Design files so this can be modified to your needs.

Information for this project can be found here:
http://www.instructables.com/id/Sensor-Array-and-Monitor/

As you can see by the instructions below, this is a rather complicated build. The instructions are general, so you will need to test fit and plan ahead. Wire routing is important so make sure you figure this out before getting too far. Once the parts are glued together, it will be difficult to make wiring changes. It is suggested to open the 123D file and you can see all the parts assembled. Viewing the assembled project in 3D may help when reading the instructions below.

Some parts need to be glued together after wiring is installed. I used the 30 AWG Si wire from Adafruit. It's small and very flexible. I didn't use the header pins on the Feather or TFT display to make the enclosure as small as possible.

Some of the parts may need some minor filing or drilled to fit properly. Test fit everything and trim so all parts fit. I have updated the 123D files with modifications I made and are included in the downloads.

First: Solder wires to the required pins on the bottom of the Feather. The wires need to be soldered to run centered from the pin holes so they match up with the holes on the inner board. Leave the wires long. They can be trimmed after the feather is put in place. Pass the wires from the Feather through the corresponding holes in the inner board, then route them back through the slot, or hole for soldering to the associated component. ( See picture below.)

Step 2: Glue the buttons to the button shelf and solder the button wiring before gluing the button shelf to the inner board. Note, the button shelf has 3 legs down that glue to the inner board. The button cover will be over the buttons and will rock back and forth on the center fulcrum when a button is pressed.

Step 3: Solder the wires to the TFT. Leave enough slack so the inner board can be installed/removed. I first planned to hot glue the TFT into place, but I decided to use small screws. The cover was modified with holes and counter sink for the screw heads. Glue the screws into the countersinks and put the nuts on the inside. The screen cover will cover the screw heads. Test fit this to make sure the screw heads do not interfere with the screen cover.

Step 4: The SPST switch grounds the Enable pin on the feather to turn off the unit. Test fit the switch. Included in the button shelf is a small block with three holes, the SPST pins will pass through these holes. Glue the block and switch in place so it can shut off the battery when the case is closed.

Step 5: Plug in the battery, route the wire and place the battery under the inner board.

Step 6: Put the button covers in place on the top cover. I used tape on the outside of the top cover to hold the button covers in place. Insert the inner board into the top cover. Fold loose wires to the TFT to make sure nothing gets pinched. The inner board will snap in place. The two dimples on the sides if the inner board will snap into the two holes in the to cover. This is a good time to test everything.

Step 7: Test fit the bottom and file if needed to fit tightly. Glue the bottom to the inner board only. The enclosure can still be opened by pulling on the bottom when the glue is cured. You can also use a small screwdriver in the side holes to help open the case.

Step 8: Glue the screen cover in place. Make sure the viewable part of the TFT is visable through the window. Glue only on the top cover and screen cover. Be careful not to get glue on the TFT display. Note: use little, or no glue on the top edge! There is only a narrow edge for glue on the top.

Solder the wires from the bottom and align them directly centered in the holes. Route the wires through the holes in the inner board. Route the wires from the Feather to the slot or other holes depending on the final connection. Note, the battery will share this space, so keep the wiring as flat as possible.

I modeled all the components not printed. These are all included in the 123D files. I arranged the components in 3D to allow for a compact size. The outer enclosure and inner supports were designed around the components.

During the build, when I had to make modifications without re-printing, I modified the 123D files with the change.
Just playing. Could be a pendant maybe?

When I started in amateur radio, I wanted to get an antenna that would not take up a lot of space but cover a lot of bands. The requirement was also that it be free standing. I ran across the AV-18AVQII antenna, and the advertising said it required no guy wires. So I bought it!

Unfortunately, when I installed it, it bowed like a banana. Reaching out to Hy-Gain, they tried to assist me in fixing the issue. The advertising was indeed incorrect, and they had that fixed, but I was still stuck with an antenna that I liked but I couldn't support properly.

I made it work, but have since moved but still wanted to stay with that premise of it being free standing. I also noticed the caps on the traps were pretty beat up and cracking, so I designed a base and cap set to help support the antenna more than the standard setup does.

Hy-Gain used what appear to be nylon spacers in the bottom of the traps, but the problem is that the spacers were too far up, so it would introduce wobble. The base caps I designed slide around the outside of the trap tube, adding better support. I did not do the same for the top trap.

The bottom cap has a slot so you can gauge how far up the tube the cap has been installed. The inside has a slot so the lower cap will still fit on the trap without having to unscrew the outside trap shell.

I wrapped the antenna tube with electrical tape to make sure the lower cap had a good tight seal around the antenna tubes. Also did the same with the top cap. I'm happy to say it has been free standing for a year without issues! I even used PLA and it has withstood summer heat and winters in the Midwest US.

title: K8400 VERTEX Raspberry Pi 2 Model B Mount

description.text:
I decided to go wireless and add Raspberry Pi to my K8400. This set of Things allows to mount Raspberry to the bottom of the printer, while keeping USB and RJ45 ports easily accessible.

The prerequisite of using this design is removing the fan from the center of the bottom panel. Check my other design http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1623399 where the fan is mounted to the side of motherboard cover, or go with the design from svdv http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:900402

Pi2 box is tight fit. You will need to slightly widen board's 4 holes to make sure M3 x 25mm bolts can pass through them. These bolts are similar to the ones used in the original spool holders of K8400. For center cover use 3M x 12mm screws. Use 3mm self locking nuts for all screws and bolts. You will need to remove Small Corner piece at the bottom of the left panel and reuse it's bolts and nuts.

The software I am planning to use is VirtualHere from https://www.virtualhere.com/ It is not free, but allows to extend USB port via network, as the result Repetier Host sees the printer as directly connected to the PC. I opted for this solution versus OctoPrint as it looks to me simpler and more reliable.

My next related project will be redesign of Power switch Thing http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1507537. I want to add power outlet to its back for Raspberry Pi's power supply. So, stay tuned.

Update (14-Jun-2016): Please use new version of pi2_box_top file. The original had issue that is now fixed.

remixed_from.title: Reprap Prusa I3 Y-axis motor mount

title: Hictop Reprap Prusa I3 Y-axis motor mount Remix

description.text:
Reprap Prusa I3 Y-axis motor mount Inspired by Barbari's design.
Id also like to thank billy619 in helping design this item. He actually has the Hictop printer.

I felt it could be stronger with a flange going the other way. The tension in the belt causes the motor to want to twist. The mount allows the flange to offset that twist.

The item can be printed in pla or abs. Motors get very hot and it was noticed the old Plexiglas motor mount was warped from being under load and hot at the same time. So abs or pteg is recommended for their higher melting point.

This should support the belt tension better with out drilling holes.
I attempted to put the flange on the bed side as well but it interfered with the sliding bed. The flange can be extended if needed.

Nuts have cutouts to be embedded in surface after printing so that its easy to tighten the screws without a wrench..

author: robinbw

description.text:
The modern day rules to this game are entirely speculative - and some day we may discover the hidden rulebook to how it was actually played during its time more than 3000 years ago. Until then, we'll just have to settle for tinkering with these little replicas and continue to reverse engineer this once-ubiquitous game.

On that note, has anyone ever taken a 3D scanner to most of the known 80-something boards that have survived and checked for 'wear spots' on the spaces to figure out which ones were most often occupied by pieces during gameplay? I'll bet it'd shed more light on our current interpretation on how the game was played. Couldn't find anything on the web that showed that kind of research. Anyways, just a thought.

If you found this useful, please share your work and be sure to peruse my other submissions which are almost as varied as they are many:

http://www.thingiverse.com/3E8/designs

Enjoy!

Hello!

This is my first thing.
I have an 3KU Delta Printer and the official endstops are some microswitchses. The printer's upper frame is a 3mm aluminium plate, and the X, Y, and Z carriages are made of the same material.
I didn't like the mechanical switches, so I designed the replace parts with optical endstop.

The endstop I used:
http://www.aliexpress.com/item/5pcs-lot-Optical-Endstop-Light-Control-Limit-Optical-Switch-for-3D-Printers-RAMPS-1-4-Free/1729261085.html?spm=2114.01010208.3.2.iWEo0d&ws_ab_test=searchweb201556_7,searchweb201602_5_10037_10017_507_10032_401,searchweb201603_2&btsid=7b263ed1-ac23-4e78-a32c-e939ab66acff

I fixed the endstop switch to the holder (the upper parts) with 2x10mm screw.
This part jumps into place, as you can see in the picture.

The lower (moving) part is a little tricky. You need a thin plastic, or metal sheet which can slide between the two parts of endstop.
I used a thin aluminium plate, and I fixed with glue.

3KU Delta Printer

description.text:
This cover protects K8400 mainboard and holds the fan and reset button. The fan was relocated from the center of the bottom panel for better airflow. Reset button was moved deeper inside to avoid pressing in accidentally.

I created X piece for convenience; keeping 4 black spacers in place while installing the cover may be difficult. Replace the original M3 x 16mm bolts with M3 x 25mm and reuse the self-locking nuts.

Keep black and red power wires of the board under the cover. They should exit from elongated opening facing power supply.
Depending of how your AC power cord is routed, you may need to slightly adjust the cover.

UPDATE: The cover limits access to the PCB pins that should be shortened during firmware update. To address this limitation in a new version of the cover I added a hole for toggle switch that should be wired to programming pins.

UPDATE 24-Jan-2017: Added new version of the cover that does not need nuts and thus is easier to install. Print with 0.3 mm resolution, brim, no support. Use M3x16mm screws.

UPDATE 17-Sep-2017: Shortened wall enforcement that was running into PCB. Removed STL files with older versions.

UPDATE 26-Nov-2017: New revision of the cover has been published.

130mm RC PLA printed Buldozer
with servo motor and gears
laptop batteries
7805 voltage regulator
"all functions" each thread and the arm.

It's an RC buldozer that i designed and made with an huxley reprap.
To make it you need :
-2x 608 bearings,
-M8 screw rod with some nuts (nylon nuts seems to fit well inside 608 bearings)
  • some tiny screws and washers
    3 servo "9gr" and two have to be modified to become "motors" (unlink the potentiometer from the last gears and cut the block that prevent it to make complete turns)
    a battery pack (mine is 2 elements 3.7V 2200mAH from a laptop battery)
    And some voltage regulator to amke 5V for the receptor.
    • Now for the mechanical part :
    Before printing make sur that you correctly positioned the part in your slicing software, some of my stl are "in the air"
    You will certainly need some wood fill mainly on the tank thread and the tooth of the "wheels" to make them run smoothly. I use "acetone " (french word for the chemical that melt the PLA) to glue all the parts together The thread are assembled with paper clip Don't forget to screw the servo before assembling and to not glue the hood and top to put batteries and electronic in it. If you have a programmable transmitter you could make mix and have on one stick all directions. By the way the thread are slipery on hard surface but on grass/earth/sand it should be fine. Oh and i forgot : it's really fun to drive and clean the mess on my desk with it ;) See it in action :
    http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zUUmX01zgo0 ps : thread inspire by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10924

title: mpCNC upgraded tool mount for dremel

description.text:
Not many to say... a quick dirty fix to apply the already designed dremel mount for the new toolplate on mpcnc.

Not printed yet... actually printing it right now.. so it not tested yet!!!

UPDATE!!! Yeap it turned out perfect (for my needs at least). I think the holes on the upper front piece to ease screwing the upper back piece needed a little better angle calibration but it was piece of cake to put it on the new toolmount of mpcnc.

As i followed the prototype's diameter i had to put a piece of anti-slip thing (photos 6,7 - like the ones we put under chair's and furniture's legs) which i had also in the previous version to fit my Digital400 Dremel. But it is tight as hell now.

Also applied this amazing dust shoe which is easy to remove at any instance and really focused to the cutting point. Haven't used the shoe yet but i am it'll be perfect!!! Under it i used super glue and fit a plastic coffee cup which ripped edges to avoid dust from spreading.

More updates for the mpcnc upgrades i've adapted on my machine, to come in this or a new post...

till then happy cutting & curving!!!

title: Convert a Fabrikator Mini into a drawing plotter

description.text:
Pen holder for the fabrikator mini (aka tinyboy) to be attached to the back of the extruder (closer side to the Y motor)

Can be used with the cura.ini profile for converting images to gcode.

then import the code into repetier, and it works fine.

Make sure in Repetier gcode editor, or in cura before exporting the gcode, to manually eliminate the homing movements just at the start of the code because the pencil will be stopping the Y and Z axis before it can touch the end-stop controller, making otherwise the motors lose steps. You would have to set up manually the zero point, at least for Y and Z, using command: G92 X0 Y0 Z0 (optionally @isathome)
see more here about setting zero manually on fabrikator-mini or any other reprap based machine on this:
reprap forum thread.

These are the two files I designed at onshape for which you can adapt the pen diameter/hexagon dimensions, then export to STL from onshape website:

Circular Pen Holder. default inner diameter = 8.8 mm

hexagonal Pen Holder.default face to face hexagon distance = 7.7 mm

Video of the machine making some drawing

description.text:
Google Image the name to find lots of photos of what this is supposed to look like completed. Still needs a bit of tweaking: I haven't worked out how to do threads yet, hence the optional knob with hex hole in it for inserting a 1/4 inch nut. Also a shaft end with a square hole through it to take a 1/4 inch coach bolt.
Obviously a cipher device is not much use without the letters on it, but not only will putting all the letters and text on the parts take ages, they'll be so small that few extruded-filament printers will be able to capture the detail at actual size (this thing is tiny). Instead the idea is to print them out on paper in columns and cut out the strips to stick onto the disc perimeters.
Of course you need to make 25 of the 'disc blanks'. And I would forget about the shaft and just use a length of 1/4 inch threaded rod, or a 4 1/2 inch long bolt. I'm speaking in ye olde imperial measurements, of course, because this gizmo was originally designed in America before WWII.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.02mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Since the real things are made of aluminium, this would look best printed in silver filament. If you can get the stuff to stick to the bed or the raft. Not that I'm having trouble or anything...

Those steps along the indicator arm could be avoided if printed on it's side.

Prints OK on the old Makerbot at work, though the 'silver' filament I'm trying to use is doing odd things on the first couple of layers. But dimensions are good and the parts fit together. Have also tried with a U-Print: outrageous cost and lousy resolution, but the support comes away more cleanly and easily.
I've included two files for printing out the lettering to go on the discs. One is a full Photoshop document for those who might want to fiddle with it, the other as a JPEG for those without Photoshop. The first/top letter (or number) in each column just identifies the disc and should be cut off. Actually, this identifier is superfluous, since each disc can be identified by the first letter to appear after the 'A'.
Cut the strips 3.5mm wide (find the 'W' in each column and cut a smidge outside it.)(Be sure to use a metric smidge, not the old imperial smidge, which is a gnat's bum too wide.)(Metric gnat's bum, obviously.) Strip length from top to bottom should of course match the circumference of the discs. About 115mm worked for mine. You should be able to cut at the bottom edge of the top letter/number (removing it) and at the bottom of the last letter.
When sticking the strips to the discs, note the 'A' always goes adjacent to the little bump inside the rim. A final layer of clear tape over the top will protect the printed lettering from wear during use.

Correction - I tried to include a JPEG, but it didn't show up as a 'file'.

I applied 'magic tape' over the lettering before cutting the strips to protect them. This is silver self-adhesive stuff that looks just like aluminium with the frosted tape on it. This is fiddly and tedious. But worth it! Be careful to glue the indicator arm to the indicator disc at a perfect right-angle. I'm using a 5inch long coach bolt here because I'm lazy and found one close to hand. You could paint the parts silver, but it wouldn't stand up to much handling. Better to print the parts in silver, or even pale grey.

There are plenty of photos of these gizmos on the Net, but very few dimensions, and surprisingly few good pics that show the details clearly. So I've used the few dimensions I could find (special thanks to a member on the cryptocollectors Yahoo group) and scaled from the photos. As a result, I dare say dimensions are slightly out, but I think it looks reasonable.
Any accurate dimensions would be greatly appreciated and incorporated into future versions.

title: Semi-Slingshot 3 mm slice 1
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Learn more about the story of the Semi-Tube Slingshot and its performance at www.slingshotforum.com. Search for 'aiping'!

Explanation:

Semi Tube Slingshot for hold right, draw left (if my brain is not twisted, if you turn
the smooth surface upside, it should become a hold left draw right slingshot)

Template 1 (the templates are printed 1 mm thick for endurance)

You need Template 1,2 and 3

Warning: Only for experienced plywood crafter !

For those who want to realize a wooden version.

The template need to be put on a 3 mm thick sheet of wood,
make sure that the smooth surface touches the wood,
the rough surface is upside, or ALL the other way round, rough downside, smooth upside for hold the slingshot left, draw right.

Than cut it out, find the right order (see screen shot), glue it together, shape and sand it.

If you use the template, please keep in mind, that the real contours of the semi-slingshot follows the inner edge of the cut-out wood steps. You may remove the outer edge of the cut-out wood steps, but than you should become stitchy. There is no 'extra meat', or you scale the printout x and y 5-10% up.

As simple it sounds, that is a lot of work!

print_settings.Notes:: The image shows the print I have done which is roughly 5 centimeters tall. It was printed at 0.2mm layer height. A few areas aren't perfect; e.g. the snout details, some parts of the legs and the tail. But these are probably due to the lack of design foresight and the shear size of the print.

description.text:
These are a set of five different animals which I designed and modeled from my imagination. I used Tinkercad, in which it took roughly half an hour to an hour each, just using simple blocks and holes.

Below are guides on how to use this project within a learning environment, be it a classroom. a club or anything in between.

Printer:

Da vinci 1.0

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm and below

Infill:

Any amount will work

Notes:

Cat:

  • The image shows the print I have done which is roughly 5 centimeters tall. It was printed at 0.2mm layer height. A few areas aren't perfect; e.g. the snout details, some parts of the legs and the tail. But these are probably due to the lack of design foresight and the shear size of the print.
  • The cat was printed with abs plastic, probably not the preferred choice for schools so I would assume a pla print at this size and scale would turn out better.

About TinkerCad

Tinkercad is a great tool for new and inexperienced designers to get familiar with the world of 3d design. It provides basic building blocks which the user reshapes and reforms into their desired result. This is unlike most mesh base modeling systems which require the use of individual points and modifiers to create a finished product and parametric or sketch based modeling systems which are often extremely complicated and hard for beginners to grasp.

Tinkercad's benefits include:

  • Being Web-based and in the cloud; the students don't need to use specific computer with the installed program, they can use their own laptops in class or even on their devices at home.
  • Tinkercad is completely free; no extra school fees mean extra school pleas.
  • Tinkercad is exceedingly simple and quick to learn: Just show the kids a bit about navigating the interface, and let them explore the rest, it's just effortless.

There are a countless number of other benefits to Tinkercad which I'm sure most of you will know so I won't bore you with them all.

The Cat as an example

An acquaintance of mine, a Chinese language teacher, will be the example for the lesson project. Their course for years 3-4 includes a major section about animals. They learn about simple questions and statements about these five animals (cats, dogs, rabbits, fish & birds).

This cat is very simple, allowing younger or newer kids to be able to do this. But note that this exact design is not necessary. It is just a concept. Individual teachers can choose what they would like the children to do and customize their amount of involvement; getting the children to follow a certain instructional guide or getting them to figure out their own designs:

  • However this comes with it's own set of hardships such as making sure they design objects which can feasibly be printed (e.g. checking for thin walls/details, size constraints, strange overhangs).
  • Thankfully most slicers will check for this and proceed to warn you before printing. There are also many fixes for these such as netfabb's model repair service which is simple, quick and reliable.

Below are a simplified version of the steps I took to design the cat, but all the animals can be found in their own 'things' here:
Cat:

  • Thingiverse
  • Tinkercad

Dog:

  • [Thingiverse](
  • [Tinkercad](

Rabbit:

  • Thingiverse
  • Tinkercad

Fish:

  • Thingiverse
  • Tinkercad

Bird:

  • [Thingiverse](
  • [Tinkercad](

I started with the basic building blocks (the head and the body). The body was rotated a bit to fit with my design concept.

I had experimented with the different ways I could position these two main body parts until I had the general concept in mind. For students, it may be a good idea to get them to draw a sketch, not necessarily a detailed one, but something to show that they have their idea in mind.
Research can also be a great thing. For instance, I went through a lot of existing models on Thingiverse and Tinkercad before drawing enough inspiration for the look I was going for.

A simple search of 'cat' will bring up a lot of great designs and ideas.

Then came the legs. They were made with a few paraboloids and stretched spheres. A great tip/technique is to create one side first then rotate, scale and stretch the parts until they look the way you want. Then copy or mirror them over to the opposite side.

The ear, as seen above, is just about the most complicated part of this design (which really isn't very complicated). It consists of a paraboloid with a larger paraboloid cutting a hole out. Simple, but effective.

The tail, which as you can see is on the surface, very scary looking, but if you look into it, it just uses the basic principles of Tinkercad. Using a premade object and cutting it with another. I then resized it and positioned it into where i wanted, but that wasn't good enough for me. So i simply proceeded to duplicated it and flip it vertically.

Here it is, all finished and with the eyes, and nose/whiskers.

From this point, it's ready to print, in fact I did just that.
The bottom of it's feet to the tip of it's tail is roughly 5cm, so it is smaller that what I assume a school would print, but not by too much. I could sparingly fit 20 of these on a 20x20 build plate and it would turn out quite well. However the joy of 3d printing is not in making many of the same small object for each child, it is the customizability and how each object can be unique to the person who created it. This is simply wonderful for the learning experiences the kids can receive but i'll talk about it further in depth later on.

Overview

Comprehension through creation is designed to be exactly as the name states. It is meant to give students a better understanding of something they are doing in class. For the year 4 class in particular, they learn about animals and phrases pertaining to them. If they went through a process of designing and creating their own animal, they will relate that to all the Chinese phrases or cultural significance they learnt along side it.

This can also be applied to older students. Take a high school class for example. Instead of just reading some Macbeth, listening to some Macbeth, then writing some Macbeth essays , it could include making some Macbeth. Creating individualized and personal representations of items, characters or even places.

HERE

Objectives
  • Students will understand the basics in the process of 3d design and creation.
    • Tinkercad and 3d printing or others depending on individual classes
    • Building elaborate designs from fundamental blocks.
  • Students will use their finished products to aid their learning further within that class. In other words, it ties in to what the class would otherwise do
    • Through their enhanced ability to 'comprehend' things such as a plot line or gives them a correlation between concepts and reality.
Audiences

As mentioned previously, the example that I am using is a 3rd-4th grade Chinese teaching curriculum. So this project is naturally designed for 3rd and 4th graders, but that doesn't mean it can't be applied to other levels of learning.

Grades 1-4

  • Children can have the most basic designing process. But still learn basic modelling by playing around and customizing pre-made objects in Tinkercad. For anybody doubting this approach, I shall explain why this makes so much sense.
    • First of all, children learn at a surprising rate when they are let to run rampant and explore however they want.
    • This is coupled with the ease of use and unnecessity to think 5 steps ahead when using Tinkercad.
    • If the kids are given a model that the teacher has chosen which is easily printed, there will probably not be much they can do to make it worse.

Grades 3-6

  • The kids can follow this plan here. But individual educators, classes, clubs or schools can feel free to change or adapt it to suit their aims and goals.

Grades 7 and up

  • This idea is still great for older kids, but they could be doing more complex things with it such as recreating scenes in stop-motion and using more complex software
Subjects

I'm just repeating myself at this point, but oh well.
This plan is specifically for a Chinese class, but can be easily adapted to any other class, the latter more so being the objective of this project.

For English

  • as stated above, can be used as a side project or part of a larger topic such as a novel study to broaden the pupils' understanding of the subject, or just help them commit the experience to memory.

For science

  • Students could be creating things such as chemical bond structures.

General

  • Children could work together to model the school's buildings and attempt to create a 3 dimensional map. Different skill levels can simply be a factor of overall quality.
  • High school for example, a design and technology class could be split into groups which all attempt to create their own version of the school. The best one could be scaled up, printed in parts and finished to be on display somewhere.
    In my school, we had a 'surviving high school' course we did two lessons a week for the first half of year 7. This course was created to help year 7's know what high school, in general, is about, but also the school specifically. We could have done a project where we model the school or parts of it, bringing us to study many different areas and helping us find our own way around the school. Something that would have been very helpful.
  • Primary school for example, a class could be split into groups with each of them doing a separate building, they could do it in class time with the teacher's guidance, and when they are all finished, they could work as a class and bring them all together on a map.
Skills learned

Students who actively go through the process of research, design, production and iteration will come to know not only the subject matter but key manufacturing principles and

I used Inkscape and GIMP to process the original image source (in-game symbol of the Redguards). Then, I modelled the pendant in Blender.

Redguards are the most naturally talented warriors in Tamriel. The dark-skinned, wiry-haired people of Hammerfell seem born to battle, though their pride and fierce independence of spirit makes them more suitable as scouts or skirmishers, or as free-ranging heroes and adventurers, than as rank-and-file soldiers. In addition to their cultural affinities for many armor styles and weapons (particularly swords), Redguards are also physically blessed with hardy constitutions, resistance to poison, and quickness of foot. Redguards do not share the same blood as the other human races, and they have no known connection with the ancestral Nordic homeland of Atmora.

Cross Section Structure model of a design for a Library in Zurich. The model is made out of 1mm and 2mm white cardboard. The seperate Pieces have to be glued or stuck together.
Lasered with a 90W CO2 Laser, you need approximately 4 hours to cut and about 40 pieces of 900x600mm cardboard.
Sticking the pieces together.

A fancy lamp with room to add your own wiring to. Improvements since the prototype:
1) Split up into four parts to allow for larger printing. Assumes a max build height of 8.5-9ish cm.
2) Base parts have threading so they just screw together. Top part is now printed upside-down to give it a nicer exterior surface.
3) Holes for wiring and adding switches.

Before you do anything, print out "thread_test.stl", and make sure that they will actually twist together snuggly but without being forced.  If they don't, you just saved yourself a few hours of printing to find out the same thing.
Next, ideally take a look in functional_lanturn.blend to get a feel for what sort of wiring and switches would fit for it.  If need be, export the base without any of the holes for threading, export the appropriate mask for the bottom half, and use openscad or another tool of your choice to take the intersection of the two, and then slice out any holes you need for electronics you would desire to use.
Thread_test.stl doesn't require supports, but the rest of the parts do.  Base_top and Vase_top may also benefit from a raft to keep parts of them from poping off the build plate while printing.
Last but not least, be prepared to waste a lot of plastic on support structures :)
Oh, and print the "vase" parts in something semi-transparent =)  If you want, that is.

title: Blue Yeti Mounting Kit - Brackets and 5/8 inch Screw
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I needed a way to attach my Blue Yeti microphone to the shock mount that I printed, so I made these parts as a sort of kit. The kit consists of a screw for the bottom mounting hole, and brackets for the two side screw holes (where the desk stand normally attaches).

It's widely known that the Blue Yeti uses a 5/8 inch "microphone stand thread" screw on the bottom for attaching to a shock mount, but beyond that I could find little information and had to resort to trial and error.

As near as I can tell, that screw needs to be UNEF (extra fine threaded, or 24 Threads Per Inch). Unfortunately, the only 5/8" screws that my hardware store carried were UNC (coarse) threaded (11 TPI), and were also more than twice the length that I needed. This would have resulted in a loose microphone and lot of unnecessary weight. Too cheap and too impatient to order one, I decided to try a printed screw instead.

Printer:

Maker Select v2 (Wanhao di3)

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1 - 0.2 (smaller for better quality threads)

Infill:

= 50%

Notes:

Support is normally needed only on the brackets (mostly for the bridge at the top). Print two copies of that part (one for each side of the microphone). I printed them solid (100% infill).

Test fit your 5/8 screw before adding the Blue Yeti to the shock mount. If the screw comes out too tight or too loose, try scaling it a little in the X and Y axes, without changing the Z axis scale. If you change the Z scale, you'll mess up the spacing between threads.

Because the screw is printed with its axis parallel to the printer's Z axis, delamination of the layers is possible if the print is weak for some reason. I included a rectangular slot through the axis of the screw for this reason. If the screw breaks off inside the Blue Yeti, a flat screwdriver or similar object can hopefully be inserted and used to turn the remainder to remove it.

If you can't get strong enough layers to support the microphone's weight when printing with the screw axis like this, you might try rotating the screw model by 90 degrees in your slicer to make it parallel to X or Y, and then printing with support. You will probably need to do some post-processing to clean up the threads in this case. I haven't needed to try this myself.

Installation

Note: the side brackets are designed for 20mm standoffs between the upper and lower frames of the shock mount, like my printed standoffs. There's a little leeway, but if your standoffs are too different, the slot likely won't line up properly with the hole in the microphone.

Due to the clearance with the shock mount screws, if you intend on using the knobs that come with the Blue Yeti's base to attach the brackets to the microphone's body, then you will want to put these on before the two M5 screws that secure the bracket to the shock mount (because there isn't much clearance between the M5 screw and the knob).

If you aren't using the knobs for this purpose, then you are free to secure the bracket to the shock mount before securing them to the microphone (or indeed, adding the mcrophone at all). This would make stringing the elastic easier

I recommend threading the 5/8" screw slowly to minimize the chance for delamination. By default it is a tight fight, but it should work (at least, mine did). Once the 5/8 screw is threaded all the way, make sure it is tight enough that the microphone doesn't rotate.

Don't forget to check out my other Blue Yeti related parts:

  • Printed Standoffs - used for spacing the shock mount inner rings
  • Microphone Stand Adapter - To attach the shock mount to a mic stand.

author: Zink_

title: Geeetech g2s Pro Frame Upgrade- Enclosure

description.text:
For a university project we upgraded the frame of the Geeetech g2s Pro Delta Printer. The main goal was to make the frame more stable and enclose the print area to increase the quality of the prints. For materials we mostly used aluminium and acrylic plates and item profiles. Water-jet/laser cutting has been used for tooling.

The original 8mm acrylic plates have been replaced by larger 4mm aluminium plates. All major holes and slots have been copied. In addition to that another aluminium plate has been added at the bottom which incorporates three adjustable feet. These three 4mm aluminium plates are connected through 6x570mm item aluminium profiles. The joints have been further tightened with 12 item angle brackets around the middle and bottom plate. In case you want to use 4mm plates as well you need to tighten the steel rods with 4mm washers as listed in the bill of materials below.

The shorts sides are enclosed with 2mm aluminium sheets and the long sides with 5mm acrylic sheets. From the front the built area can be accessed through an acrylic door and from the sides through two sliding doors which can be locked in place with a self-designed 3D-printed knob at the upper acrylic panel.

The bottom compartment is easy to access and offers plenty of space and mounts for cable management and electronics including the Raspberry Pi for Octoprint.

Overall from all these measures the printer became extremely stable and keeps the print area protected and noticeably warmer. Moreover, the printer looks even better now.

Besides the frame, work has been done as well in regards to temperature control, wifi connectivity and filament extrusion control. For this reason, at this point plenty of cables are still hanging around as it can be seen in the pictures. The holes for the top fan as well as the door magnet are not included in the drawings as you probably find your individual solutions for that.

This project is work in process. However, all files uploaded here already include the latest updates. Nevertheless, if you plan on doing the same just double check the most important holes and slots before cutting to avoid any waste material. If you find any mistakes or improvements do not hesitate to write it in the comments. In addition to that, if you need any other files I will try my best to catch up with that.

Have fun building and printing!

description.text: This is a modular adjustable door sweep designed to be printed out of a flexible material like Nylon or NinjaFlex. The three slots allow for individual sections to be adjusted for both height and angle so that they can be tailored to glide over an uneven floor. Each is 200mm in length so 4 of them are needed to fit a standard door. When attaching them gently tighten the center screw first until there is just enough friction to keep the sweep parallel to the floor and as low as it will go. Then open and close the door once. This will adjust the sweep to the highest position needed to clear the floor. After that tighten the center and outer two screws. The sweep should now be as low as possible without catching on the floor.

title: Kossel Delta 200mm Round Bed Clamps, FSR Compatible

description.text: This week I designed a set of glass bed clamps for a Kossel Mini with a 200mm round glass bed that are compatible with a force sensitive resistor bed leveling system. The clamps are each comprised of two printed pieces, two M3x20 screws, two M3 wingnuts, and two 1/4" x 13/32" compression springs. The springs allow you to carefully adjust the tension of the clamp on the bed to make sure that the glass is held steady without holding it too tight and inadvertently triggering the resistors. Also, I've found that adjusting the tension on each can help dial in how much force is required to trigger the resistor. The pass through holes allow the position to be adjusted with the clamp assembled. When installing make sure to use a washer in the mounting slot to prevent binding and to make for correct screw depth.

Use a razor blade to remove printed brim before assembling clamps.
Designed in Autodesk Design 123D.
